"{\n  \"type\": \"theorem\",\n  \"name\": \"Maximum Distance on Ellipsoid\",\n  \"Hypothesis\": [],\n  \"Conclusion\": \"The points (1, 0, 0) and (-1, 0, 0) on the ellipsoid  \\( x^{2}+2 y^{2}+3 z^{2}=1 \\) have the largest distance from the origin.\",\n  \"Status\": \"proved\",\n  \"Proof\": {\n    \"type\": \"proof\",\n    \"Steps\": [\n      {\n        \"type\": \"remark\",\n        \"Statement\": \"We will use the fact that the distance from a point  (x, y, z) to the origin is given by \\(  \\\\sqrt{x^2 + y^2 + z^2} \\). To simplify calculations, we will maximize the square of the distance,  \\( x^2 + y^2 + z^2 \\), since maximizing a function is equivalent to maximizing its square over a domain with nonnegative values.\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"type\": \"let\",\n        \"Variable\": \"f(x, y, z)\",\n        \"Value\": \"x^2 + y^2 + z^2\",\n        \"Kind\": \"function\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"type\": \"remark\",\n        \"Statement\": \"We want to maximize f(x, y, z) subject to the constraint that (x, y, z) lies on the ellipsoid \\( x^{2}+2 y^{2}+3 z^{2}=1 \\).\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"type\": \"remark\",\n        \"Statement\": \"We are given that any continuous function on the ellipsoid attains its maximum. Since the distance function is continuous, and the ellipsoid is a closed and bounded set, the maximum distance must be achieved at some point on the ellipsoid.\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"type\": \"missing\",\n        \"Statement\": [\n          {\n            \"type\": \"problem\",\n            \"Statement\": \"Use Lagrange multipliers or another optimization technique to find the points on the ellipsoid  \\( x^{2}+2 y^{2}+3 z^{2}=1 \\) that maximize \\( f(x,y,z) = x^2 + y^2 + z^2 \\).\"\n          }\n        ]\n      },\n      {\n        \"type\": \"conclude\",\n        \"Statement\": \"The points that maximize the distance are (1, 0, 0) and (-1, 0, 0), completing the proof.\"\n      }\n    ]\n  }\n}"